	abstract = {It is a strategic decision how people find their place in digital media platforms. Such decisions are navigated by structures of power and social constructions like culture, class, gender, media, technology, and individual maneuvers. {TikTok} has been a haven for everyday people in Turkey. This study analyzed how and why that is the case. Looking at the content on {TikTok} and critically engaging with discursive practices around {TikTok} and {TikTokers}, this chapter argues that “cringe” people, who do not share a specific taste and cultural capital, show their presence in {TikTok} due to technological affordances {TikTok} offers, the cultural climate in other platforms, and the carnivalesque which they experience on {TikTok}. It might look like they are only producing dance or dubbing videos, but they claim a cultural sphere. The mediation of this culture, however, is sometimes encouraging and empowering, and sometimes is toxic. © Peter Lang {GmbH} Internationaler Verlag der Wissenschaften Berlin 2021.},
