	abstract = {This study examined two ways of using the {TikTok} application (active vs. passive use), and their association with female users' self-esteem pertaining to appearance and weight. By adopting a cross-sectional online survey design, this study recruited 7,750 adult female {TikTok} users from China (Douyin), and acquired self-reported data on 2 ways of using {TikTok}, state-level social comparison, appearance-esteem, weight-esteem, body mass index, and age. The results indicated that passive and active {TikTok} uses were negatively and positively associated with participants' appearance- and weight-esteem, respectively. A mediation analysis revealed that the participants' state-level social comparison while using {TikTok} mediated the association between two ways of {TikTok} use, and their effects on appearance- and weight-esteem. These results help us understand the complicated impact of {TikTok} use on body image, and design campaigns for promoting body acceptance.  © Copyright 2023, Mary Ann Liebert, Inc., publishers 2023.},
